SIMPLE: niggard
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Niggard
<hw>Nig"gard</hw> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧g"g⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Icel. <ets>hn⟦oum⟧ggr</ets> niggardly, stingy + <ets>-ard</ets>;
cf. Sw. <ets>njugg</ets>, AS. <ets>hne⟦aacute⟧w</ets>.]</ety> <def>A
person meanly stingy and covetous; one who spends grudgingly; a stingy,
parsimonious fellow; a miser.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A penurious <qex>niggard</qex> of his wealth.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>niggards</qex> of advice on no pretense.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Niggard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Niggard
<hw>Nig"gard</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a niggard; meanly covetous or
parsimonious; niggardly; miserly; stingy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Niggard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Niggard
<hw>Nig"gard</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To act the niggard toward;
to be niggardly.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Niggardise</ent>⟦br⟧
